[2026-03-10T15:55:37Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014mQRvJuWoDaARVfinDod57","type":"tool_result","content":"    45→Takes a `Task` and project context, calls the project's configured LLM to generate\n    46→a prompt suitable for the workflow. The generated prompt is passed to the workflow run\n    47→as the `--prompt` argument.\n    48→\n    49→### Orchestration Loop\n    50→\n    51→Event-driven, triggers on:\n    52→1. Daemon startup — check all projects for ready work.\n    53→2. Run completion — after a run finishes, check the completed run's project for more work.\n    54→3. `cloche orchestrate` CLI command — manual trigger, checks all projects.\n    55→\n    56→On trigger:\n    57→1. For each registered project with orchestration enabled:\n    58→2. Query task tracker for ready work (priority-ordered).\n    59→3. Check in-flight run count against per-project concurrency limit.\n    60→4. For each available slot: claim the highest-priority task, generate prompt, dispatch run.\n    61→\n    62→### Configuration\n    63→\n    64→Per-project in `.cloche/config.toml` (or similar):\n    65→\n    66→```toml\n    67→[orchestration]\n    68→enabled = true\n    69→tracker = \"beads\"\n    70→concurrency = 1\n    71→workflow = \"develop\"\n    72→```\n    73→\n    74→### Concurrency\n    75→\n    76→Per-project limits. Project A with limit 2 and project B with limit 1 can have up to\n    77→3 runs in-flight simultaneously.\n    78→\n    79→### Merge Queue\n    80→\n    81→When a run completes successfully (`done` result), the orchestrator enqueues its\n    82→branch (`cloche/<runID>`) into a per-project merge queue.\n    83→\n    84→**Serialization:** Per-project. Each project processes one merge at a time. Different\n    85→projects can merge in parallel. Queue is FIFO.\n    86→\n    87→**Merge execution:** The orchestrator picks the next branch from the queue and hands\n    88→it to an LLM agent running on the host (not in a container). The agent operates in\n    89→a git worktree and:\n    90→\n    91→1. Pulls latest main into the worktree.\n    92→2. Merges the feature branch.\n    93→3. Resolves any conflicts.\n    94→4. Runs validation if configured (tests, build).\n    95→5. If clean: merges to main, cleans up the worktree, deletes the branch.\n    96→6. If unresolvable: reports failure.\n    97→\n    98→**On the host via worktree:** Merges need direct access to the real git repo. A git\n    99→worktree is created for the merge, then removed after completion. Lighter weight\n   100→than spinning up a container.\n   101→\n   102→**Failure handling:** If the merge agent can't resolve conflicts, the merge is marked\n   103→as failed. The branch is preserved. The user is notified via the dashboard/indicator\n   104→lights. No automatic retry — human intervenes.\n   105→\n   106→**Post-merge:** After a successful merge, the branch is deleted and the orchestrator\n   107→triggers a check for more work (same event-driven model as run completion).\n   108→\n   109→---\n   110→\n   111→## 2. Indicator Lights\n   112→\n   113→**Goal:** Per-project health indicators based on recent run history.\n   114→\n   115→### Health Calculator\n   116→\n   117→Domain-level function: given the last N runs for a project, return health status:\n   118→- **Green** — all runs passed\n   119→- **Yellow** — some runs failed\n   120→- **Red** — all runs failed\n   121→- **Grey** — no runs yet\n   122→- **Blue** — all runs currently in-progress (no completed runs in window)\n   123→\n   124→Window size N is configurable per-project, default 5."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01EmNnibDiBApwUA2G3spKT8","session_id":"d065b4bd-561d-4d97-a269-c4a0bb94c829","uuid":"07404694-93f2-4683-8b76-400ba4bca9d5"}
